social_posts.post_text: This tropical goddess of mine is on fire!

I am over the moon from learning that our Eco-Hero "Wild Florida" documentary that aired last night beat every primetime network show on NBC (Chicago Med), CBS (Survivor) and FOX (The Masked Singer)! Thank you to all who tuned in and to the amazing team that I was privileged to work with that was responsible for producing such a quality program!  Special thanks to WPLG News Director Bill Pohovey for believing in me and this dream I had of creating the Eco-Hero series.  Extra special thanks to all who have donated to the Ron Magill Conservation Endowment that helped fund this project and make it a reality!

(1/2) Happy Earth Day!  Here are some shots I captured Thursday of wildlife, other than wood storks, at Wakodahatchee Wetlands!  It's now the tail end of the season and most of the wood stork chicks will be fledgling within the next couple of weeks.  I'll do another post featuring just wood storks.  It had rained a bit in the early morning so it was not packed as it often is and it provided a wonderful time just enjoying and photographing wildlife! #earthday #nikonphotography #nikonnofilter #nikonambassador #floridawildlife

(1/2): Wood storks are a key indicator species regarding the health of the Everglades.  It is believed that they have the fastest known reflex action of any animal in the world.  As they partially open their bills underwater in search of food, they wait to feel a fish touch their bill and in .25 milliseconds, they close that bill, trapping the fish!  That is more than 100 times faster than a human can blink an eye! As I captured these images at Wakodahatchee, they appeared to be thriving as most are quickly approaching the time when they will fledge.  It can be incredibly loud as the chicks are constantly vocalizing, begging for food.  Ironically, as they become adults, wood storks lose most of their ability to vocalize, and are relatively silent except for a rare hiss, grunt or bill clap. #nikonphotography #nikonnofilter #nikonambassador #floridawildlife #birdphotography

Yesterday, Zoo Miami's North American river otter pups made their exhibit debut.  I've attached some images that I was able to capture of them this morning as they explored their habitat with their mom.  They will be given access off and on for limited times during the next several days until the keepers are confident that they can navigate the habitat safely.  These pups were born back on February 5th and have been bonding with their mother in a secluded holding area where she has slowly introduced them to water and initiated swimming lessons for the last several weeks.  They are now at the stage where staff feels confident that they can participate in "advanced" swimming lessons and therefore will be seen on exhibit more frequently moving forward.  It's tough getting images of them through thick glass with hard water stains and harsh light, but I still thought these were cute enough to share! #nikonphotography #nikonnofilter #nikonambassador #otters

I am over the moon after just being notified that my image of a jaguar has been chosen as the cover shot for the next issue of the Association of Zoos and Aquarium's (AZA) "Connect" magazine!  #nikonphotography #nikonnofilter #nikonambassador #bigcats #wildlifephotography

During my recent trip to Gainesville, I was able to take some time and visit Paynes Prairie State Preserve.  I had spent many days and nights in this beautiful place as a UF student working at the Florida State Museum.  Collected countless snakes, lizards and frogs for the museum and typed thousands of tags to label them.  Great memories from over 40 years ago.  From the beautiful open prairies that are still home to bison and wild horses, to the amazing oak and pine forests draped in Spanish moss and the variety of animals living there, it is a Florida treasure. #wildflorida

Last Friday, a team from Zoo Miami transported a loggerhead sea turtle from Zoo Miami's Sea Turtle Hospital to a special facility at Advanced Veterinary Specialists in Davie, FL to receive a CT scan.  The turtle had been rescued from the Deering Estate after getting tangled in buoy line and was suffering from tumors caused by the fibropapilloma virus.  The scan was to see if the tumors had spread to internal organs.  Initial indications are that it may have indeed spread to internal organs which is not good news for this endangered animal. 😔

What an incredible surprise it was to see an old friend today whom I hadn’t seen in many years!  Michael Gerlach was by far one of the smartest animal people I have ever worked with.  He, along with two other co-workers, Carl Burch and Dr. Gordon Hubbell, were my most important mentors when I started working at the Crandon Park Zoo over 43 years ago.  No one had better animal sense, especially with hoofstock, than Michael.  He taught me so much about how to read animals and safely handle them.  Seeing him today brought back so may wonderful memories.  From fishing for tarpon with him while doing night duty at Crandon Park, to watching him lure an escaped lion back to its enclosure while holding a piece of meat and driving a golf cart, Michael is an indelible part of some of the best experiences I’ve ever had at the zoo.  Though I may not have realized it back then, I was extremely lucky to work with him and profoundly grateful for all he taught me!

After months of renovations and upgrades, Zoo Miami’s Black Rhino barn and habitat has been reopened and has welcomed back its first black rhino!  Yesterday, “Eddie,” a 23 year-old male, was given access to his new yard for the first time.  As he carefully explored his new upgrades, he first enjoyed the new vegetation that had grown on top of the rockwork during his absence.  He then went around the entire habitat, carefully spraying the rockwork with his urine to mark his territory!  One of the most significant changes to the habitat is the conversion of the old pools into clay wallows.  Though initially hesitant to step onto the clay, his curiosity eventually got the best of him!  As he stepped in for the first time, his tremendous weight caused his thick legs to sink a foot or so into the clay, much like walking in deep snow.  Though it startled him at first, he soon adjusted and eventually was walking throughout the wallow.  He was given access over-night and must have truly enjoyed the wallow because this morning he was covered in clay and may be better referred to from now as a “Red Rhino!” I’ve attached some images that I was able to capture of him as he first stepped out to the new habitat to explore it (may be the last images of him showing his natural grey color!) and then venturing into the clay pit for the first time.  There are also some follow-up images of him this morning showing his “conversion” from black rhino to “red” rhino!” #nikonambassador #nikonnofilter #nikonphotography

Here are some images that I was able to capture this morning of our newest marabou stork chicks with my new Nikon Z8 mirrorless camera!  These chicks hatched on May 11th and 12th and are being successfully raised by their experienced parents!  The father is 31 years old and the mother is almost 20 years old.  This pair has successfully raised a single chick in 2021 and another in 2022.  I want to give a special shout out to Matt McCale for making it possible for me to get these images!
 
Some polls having given the Marabou stork the distinguished status of being recognized as the “ugliest bird in the world.” However, with a more positive perspective, one may consider them to be so ugly that they are cute!  According to African legend, God ran out of animal parts while producing the creatures of Africa and decided to use the leftover bird parts to create the unsightly marabou stork. 
 
The marabou is the largest flying stork in the world and is commonly found throughout sub-Saharan Africa.  It is primarily a scavenger though it is also known for feeding on smaller reptiles, eggs and the chicks of other birds.  It is often referred to as the “Undertaker Bird,” not so much for its habit of feeding on the dead, but more so for its physical resemblance to the “grim reaper” hunched over while wearing a dark cloak with a bald head and long beak!  In addition to their unattractive habit of feeding on rotting carcasses, they also will defecate on their own legs, depending on the subsequent evaporation to help keep them cool.  Having said all of this, it is important to remember that even with all of the associated repulsiveness, these massive birds play a critical role in preventing the spread of disease and helping to keep the world a cleaner place for the rest of us!
 
Have a great weekend!

Had the opportunity last weekend to spend some time at Flamingo Gardens after I was honored to give a presentation to their camera club.  Thanks to Laura Wyatt, I was able to be introduced to some of their beautiful animals, including some stunning birds.  I took my newly acquired Nikon Z8 to give it a quick test and couldn't be happier with the results!  From peregrines to peacocks, it captured them beautifully! #beautifulbirds #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikonambassador

In honor of our amazing hockey team, I photographed this stunning Florida Panther during a recent visit to Flamingo Gardens here in South Florida. Shot with my new Nikon Z8, the focus and intensity of its look is a reflection of our NHL team and I love as it salivates looking towards the Stanley Cup! Go Panthers! #floridawildlife #floridapanther #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikonambassador

One of the greatest joys of wildlife photography is when all of the stars align. Having the right lighting, being in the right position, and having the right equipment while the animals do their thing! I had been trying to get this image of this pair of Sumatran tigers breeding for years! It is rare that they are actually put together as tigers are solitary, and if you put them together at the wrong time, it could result in serious injury or even death. Our female, Leeloo, is very high strung and has, shall we say, not a very nice personality! Our male, Berani, is getting up in age and unfortunately, does not have a lot of "swimmers," if you know what I mean, so this breeding may not be successful. Nevertheless, it is intense and an adrenaline rush to observe! There is an entire series of images that I captured of this encounter but this is the single image that stands out for me. It happened so quickly and my Nikon Z8 immediately locked on Berani's eyes and captured this split second moment! The intensity of his eyes as he roars loudly as if to say, "I AM THE MAN!!!!!" while she seems to have a "Are you done yet?" look is classic! Over the years, I have caught them breeding but it was always an obstructed view or they were facing away or the lighting was too dark or too harsh. This morning, after flirting with him all morning and then only going back into the night house to breed, Leeloo finally came out and presented her rear end right into Berani's face (she gets VERY promiscuous when she cycles!) facing me in a clear area! It was a perfect overcast sky with nice even lighting, and I pointed my Z8 with a Nikon AFS200-500mm lens while pressing the shutter and BAM!!!!!!! A very visual definition of "dong the wild thing!" Have a great and safe holiday weekend! #wildlifephotography #bigcats #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikonambassador
Proud to have this hanging in my office!  Go Heat!  Four more!

After working at the zoo for over 43 years, I wanted to produce something that I felt reflected the reasons why I came to work here in the first place.  Something that was more than the typical tourist commercial that are often more focused on the attraction, rather than the institution.  I spent many hours capturing the shots featured in this video, often on my days off, and tried to put into words what I felt were the most important features of Zoo Miami.  I want to thank my son, Sean Magill (@sean_magill) for helping me to produce what was a labor of love for me.  I hope that it is something that brings about a sense of pride to all of us who have dedicated so much to this important institution.  Special thanks to Nikon for providing me with the equipment that made it possible to capture most of these images! #wildlifeconservation #zoomiami #wildlifephotography #nikoncreators

This weekend, a wonderful high energy show opened at Zoo Miami! "Canine Champions for Conservation" is an exciting presentation featuring adopted and rescued dogs from all over the country. Here are some images that I captured from their first performances! Their behaviors demonstrate amazing physical speed and coordination as they chase frisbees, race through an obstacle course, jump rope, and local hidden scents. The bond and trust between them and their trainers is inspiring. Hopefully, guests who watch the show will be inspired to want to rescue and/or adopt one of the countless dogs being held in shelters around the country. They truly are "man's best friend!" So happy to have my Nikon Z8 lock on to the eye of these dogs and keep the shots in focus! #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikoncreators

Walking early in the morning with my camera and nothing but the sights and sounds of nature is the best medicine there is! The beauty and diversity of Florida wildlife is priceless! #floridawildlife #nikonphotography #nikonambassador

In honor of "Nature Photography Day," here are a few that I have been lucky to capture over the years from around the world. Thank you Nikon! #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikonambassador #wildlifephotography

On Tuesday, I was privileged to participate in the release of two adult loggerhead sea turtles on a beach in Naples, FL. Both of these turtles were brought to Zoo Miami's Sea Turtle Hospital suffering from exposure to Red Tide. They were anemic, emaciated and covered with barnacles and algae. After months of daily care by Zoo Miami's Animal Health Team, they made a full recovery and were successfully released close to where they were originally rescued. Nothing feels better than this when it comes to wildlife conservation and it is what makes me proud to work at the zoo! I love documenting these stories! #seaturtleconservation #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikonambassador

Today, I once again had the privilege of granting a wish for a beautiful young lady on behalf of the Make-A-Wish Foundation.  This family from Tennessee is full of beautiful ladies and these sisters are just two examples.  Ten year old Carina and nine year old Taleah, are absolute joys!  Their smiles were the highlight of my day as i granted Taleah’s wish to meet and feed a sloth!  I pray that Taleah will overcome the life-threatening challenges she is facing. 🙏🏻

Gorgeous weather and breathtaking vistas with my two favorite ladies in Yosemite National Park!  From mind-blowing rock formations and mirrored lakes, to endless stunning waterfalls and ancient massive Sequoias, this natural treasure provides awe-inspiring experiences at every turn!  Lots of pics to come!  Happy Fourth!
The wild flowers are in full bloom in parts of Yosemite National park, surrounding the most beautiful flower of all!😊❤️

Yosemite has an incredible amount of amazing vistas at practically every turn. After a record snowfall this past winter, the myriad of waterfalls, including Yosemite Falls, Ribbon Falls, and Vernal Falls, were running at full blast! #yosemitenationalpark #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikonambassador

Yosemite National Park has many iconic features but the massive Fock formations and outcrops with names such as 'El Capitan," "Half Dome," and "Tunnel View," stand out as the most well recognized. With many views from different perspectives, this national treasure is a photographer's paradise! #yosemitenationalpark #elcapitan #halfdome #tunnelview #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikonambassador

Whether it is the reflections of the dramatic rock formations in mirror lakes or the soothing sounds of rushing rivers and streams, water plays a major role in sculpting and reflecting the beauty of Yosemite. We were lucky to be there when the water was a plentiful and the weather was perfect! #yosemite #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikonambassador

While on the west coast, I made a stop at the L.A. Zoo to capture some images of animals that we don't have at Zoo Miami. One of my priorities was the California condor. This is an animal that would be extinct were it not for zoos breeding them under human care and successfully releasing them back to the wild. It serves as a prime example of a zoo success story and why zoos are important. #californiacondor #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikonambassador

I have always been fascinated with snakes. Since my first paid job working with animals at the Miami Serpentatrium in the 70's, venomous snakes have bee a special interest. And of all of the venomous snakes, I find few more beautiful and impressive than the gaboon viper! As a 22 year old single guy, I bred and raised these amazing snakes. I couldn't help but snap a pic of this one at the Los Angeles Zoo during my recent visit. With the longest fangs of any snake and a stunning pattern that blends right into the forest floor, they are nature's artwork personified! #beautifulsnake #NikonPhotography #nikonusa #nikonambassador

The Stellar's Sea Eagle is arguably the largest eagle in the world! It resembles a bald eagle on steroids with many of the same behaviors and feeding techniques. With females weighing close to 20 pounds this massive raptor is never found far from water in Japan, Russia, China and Korea where it feeds primarily on fish. I felt fortunate to be able to get some decent shots of this individual during my recent visit to the L.A. Zoo. #birdphotography #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikonambassador
Images that I was a able to capture of animals cooling off in this unprecedented heat at Zoo Miami.

Incredibly privileged to welcome some of the Nikon geniuses from Japan and New York to teach and introduce me to some of the upcoming technology that will help change the face of wildlife photography!  I will be forever indebted to Nikon, and especially to @corradophotography for the privilege of being part of the greatest photographic family in the world! #nikonphotography #nikonambassadr

Today, our family lost our matriarch and the most amazing mother, grandmother, great-grandmother, sister, mother-in-law, aunt and friend that anyone could hope to have. After more than 92 years of bringing love and joy to so many, she finally went to join the love of her life, my dad, so that they could start the party all over again, and together, look over us from up above. It has been a heart-wrenching week for all of us but we gain our strength from this amazing woman who made us promise to never mourn her passing but to only celebrate her life. As my eyes well up while writing this, I also have a simultaneous smile knowing how incredibly lucky we have all been to be loved by this most incredible woman and how the last thing she would want is to see us sad. My sister and I are who we are today because of our parents who sacrificed so much to give us this phenomenal life that we are so blessed to have. My mom was always the rock for all of us and made sure that we never forget that there is nothing more important than family. Though my parents are no longer physically with us, they will continue to live in us and we will continue to honor and love them through what we do every day to continue their profound legacy of love. As my mom always said, "true love never dies." 💔🙏❤️

On behalf of our family, I want to thank everyone for the outpouring of love and support we have received over the passing of my mom. So many have asked about services so I wanted to share my mom's wishes which we are following:
My mom made it very clear to us that she didn't want any services, flowers, etc. She didn't want anyone to mourn her passing. She said what would make her happy would be to: "Do something you love with someone you love." That would be the best way that you could honor her memory so I urge you all to do just that. I believe that is what she is now doing with my father in heaven. 🙏❤🙏
In honor of my mom, “ doing something I love, with someone I love.” 🙏🏻❤️
This……❤️
To the world, you are a person but to me, you are the world! Happy Birthday my love!

Yesterday, Zoo Miami's 8-month-old giraffe named, "Turtle" (I have no idea how he got that name!), had surgery to remove a bone fragment from his right rear leg that was causing severe pain in his joint. In what is one of the most challenging immobilizations in the zoo, the incredible team of over a dozen people worked like a finely tuned machine to get the job done! Thanks to veterinary equine specialist, Dr. Alexander Daniel and his team for volunteering their time to perform the surgery with the assistance of our Animal Health Team! In addition to the surgery, the procedure included radiographs, acupuncture, laser therapy and massage therapy! I'm happy to say that today, "Turtle" is standing and walking normally!

Super excited to head to New York to present alongside some of the world's most amazing photographers! If you are in NYC on Wednesday or Thursday, stop by the Jacob Javitz Center for what is sure to be lots of amazing photographic experiences! #nikonphotography #nikonambassador

An incredible evening last night celebrating the Bild Expo at the Jacób Javits Center in New York with some of the world’s most amazing photographers!  Here I am with arguably the world’s greatest wedding photographer, and fellow Nikon Ambassador, the legendary @jerryghionis, receiving our “Creator’s Award,” along with other speakers, in front of well over 1,000 people! #nikonambassador #nikonambassador
A great night celebrating legendary glades man, Ron Bergeron's 80th birthday at a fantastic party filled with great food, drink, music fireworks, and most importantly, good friends!

Thankful to CBS 4 News Miami for having me on this morning to speak about why having a water park at Zoo Miami is a bad idea. I believe we are making a difference because as I attended the Board of County Commissioners meeting this morning, I received indications from several commissioners that they may in fact vote in our favor to deny the extension for the project, in effect, killing it. This could be historic for all of us who are fighting to protect our priceless natural treasures. The vote has been deferred to December 12th. From now until then, we must not take our foot of the gas. I have requested to personally meet with each Commisioner to ensure they are aware of all the facts! It’s going to be an uphill battle, but I am so inspired by everyone who has rallied behind our effort! We’ve got to believe we can make a difference! #wildlifeconservation

Sent my photo book on the amazing show "Allura"at the Faena Theater to the publisher today! I was incredibly happy with the images my Nikon Z9 mirrorless camera was able to capture in incredibly low light! Being able to set the ISO up as high as 10,000 to have a fast shutter speed and freeze action was key. Also, the autofocus was spot on in low light with almost perfect eye-detection! With minimal post editing, I was able to capture images like this with only very low existing light. These Nikon mirrorless cameras continue to amaze me and redefine photography! I'm usually only comfortable photographing wildlife, but this was fun!!!! #nikonphotography #nikonambassador #nikonnofilter

Though the rain can be a bit of a hassle for some, others love it! During a break in the storms, "Peggy," one of our African elephants, coats herself with mud by gathering it in her trunk and then blowing it all over her body. It helps keep her cool, acts like a sunscreen (when it's out!), and also will help protect against biting insects! #loveelephants #nikonphotography #nikonnofilter #nikonambassador

Many people don't realize that birds do not produce blue pigment. In fact, when you see blues or any colors associated with blue, those colors are actually produced by refracted light through the structure of the feather. Birds consciously move their feathers to produce those colors. I was finally able to document that phenomenon with this starling. Just by pivoting his posture, his feathers go from black to vibrant! So cool! #beautyofbirds #feathers #nikonphotography

As promised, here is the reveal of the animal that I spent hours yesterday trying to photograph! It is a White Faced Saki monkey! Thanks to all the folks that guessed from my previous post! White Faced Sakis are arboreal monkeys that are found in the tropical forests of Venezuela, Guyana, French Guiana, Brazil and Suriname. They are known for their ability to jump up to 30 feet between trees as they traverse the forest canopy where they feed mostly on fruits, seeds, nuts and invertebrates. Distinguished by their thick fur and bushy tails, adults grow to between 3-4 pounds. Adult males are generally a bit larger than females and are distinguished by their black fur and white faces whereas the females are generally brown to gray without the white face. Their main predators are large birds of prey, jaguars, ocelots and large constrictor snakes. We still are not sure of this newborn's gender but will hopefully be able to get a closer look in the near future as the baby becomes more comfortable with its surroundings and mom lets it become more visible! #monkeybabychallenges #nikonphotography #nikonnofilter #nikonambassador
Some more images of that elusive newborn White Faced Saki monkey that I spent hours trying to photograph yesterday as its protective mother kept it well covered!

What a great night at the Faena Theater tonight as Rita and I were honored to present the photo book I published to the amazing cast and crew of “Allura Cabaret.” It has been such a privilege to be given special access to these incredible performers and get to know them in a more personal way. Their commitment to their artistry is beyond impressive. Their elegance, passion, sensuality and amazing athleticism make “Allura” an unforgettable experience that will seduce you! I’ll be posting some of the images I was able to capture of these fantastic artists soon! Go see this show!!

Súper excited to wake up this morning and find out the “Eco-Hero: Wild Florida” documentary that I was privileged to do with Kristi Krueger, Michelle Lacamoire and Bill Damas from WPLG Local 10, has been nominated for an Emmy in the Environment/Science category!! #WildFlorida #LetThemThrive

Today, guests at the zoo got a very special treat as our endangered banteng, "Phyllis," decided that she was going to give birth on exhibit in front of the public! As they watched in amazement, Phyllis delivered her calf without incident. She attentively cleaned it and after the newborn tried multiple times to stand on its own, she helped it to its feet where it found her teats and eagerly nursed! This is a special birth for Phyllis has her two previous pregnancies resulted in stillbirths. Though this calf appears healthy, a neonatal exam will be done within the next 48 hours to help ensure that it is progressing normally. I have been privileged to witness well over 100 births in my career and can say without hesitation that it never gets old! Banteng are a highly endangered wild cow from Southeast Asia and Indonesia where there are believed to be less than 8,000 left in the wild. Born a chestnut brown color, they soon develop white stockings and a white rump in their first year. Males will turn to an almost black color once they reach sexual maturity. Thier biggest threats are habitat loss and hunting, as well as disease introduced through domestic livestock. Here are some pics that I was able to capture of the event with my new Nikkor Z 180mm-600mm lens! This lens is THE BOMB!!! 😊 #nikonphotography #nikonnofilter #nikonambassador

The absolute bright spot of my week! I received a special package today from UPS and when I opened it, this is what I found. This wonderful little girl named Charlotte, who lives in Atlanta and has been following me for a while, decided to have a bake sale in front of her home to raise money for my conservation endowment here at the zoo. She raised hundreds of dollars out of this initiative and made sure that her father sent me the actual cash that they raised! More than the money, the photos and her cards mean more to me than she will ever know! We need more of this in our world today. 🙏

Today, I had the wonderful surprise of being visited by Naia and Shanti Haast! I’ve had the pleasure of knowing these two ladies for over 45 years when I started working for their father, the legendary Bill Haast, and their amazing mother, the stunning Clarita Haast, at the Miami Serpentarium. It’s incredible how fast time flies but so great to remember the many memories we created back in the “good ole’ days!” I still have their father’s portrait that he dedicated to me, proudly hanging in my office.

I am super excited to share this recent segment that I did with Lester Holt for the NBC Nightly News Kids Edition! I have been fortunate to have done several pieces with Lester in the past and always feel so lucky when I am asked to appear with him. I am incredibly excited to officially announce the launch of a book that Miami Herald columnist Greg Cote and I have been working on for nearly a year! “The Pride of a Lion: K’wasi’s Story – What the Animal Kingdom can teach us about survival, fear and family” is in part, the story of the first male lion cub to ever be born at Zoo Miami and the profound challenges he faced in his struggle to survive. It is the most emotional roller coaster that I have ever experienced in my over 40 years of working with animals and I wouldn’t have believed it had I not seen it and photographed it myself. It brought me from tremendous highs to devastating lows and back up again. Begrudgingly, at Greg’s insistence, it is also a story about me, and the path that has led me to live the dream that has been my career. From being born into a small apartment in NYC to traveling around the globe to study the wonders of our natural world, I share with Greg some of the very impactful experiences that have shaped my life. Though I was apprehensive about making this book as much a biography about me as it is about K’wasi, I do hope that it will inspire others to learn to love wildlife and want to protect it.
I was blown away to find out that though the book was just announced for “pre-order” (it doesn’t officially get released until December 5th), it already made the top of Amazon’s “Best-Seller” list in the category of Cats, Lions, and Tigers! What I truly love about this book is that it is under 200 pages and is an easy read that most should be able to get done in an afternoon and perfect for a plane flight! It also includes some of the many photos that I captured documenting K’wasi’s story that I know any animal lover will truly enjoy and be awed by. Greg and I will be going on a book tour soon with a special event at the zoo as well as Books & Books in Coral Gables so look out for those dates! Today, Zoo Miami’s pair of howler monkeys that reside in the Amazon and Beyond Cloud Forest habitat, underwent routine physical exams as part of a carefully managed preventative medicine program. 
Both individuals went through a series of radiographs, had their blood collected and had general dental exams as well as ultrasounds to evaluate organ health. Both individuals have since been returned to their habitat where they are recovering from the procedures without incident.
Black howler monkeys are the largest primates found in Tropical American forests. In addition to the males being much larger than the females, they are one of the few primates where the females have a very different coat color that the males. Females are a blonde to light brown color and the males are black. They have a prehensile tail which plays a major role in their ability to maneuver through the canopy of the forest where they feed on a variety of leaves, flowers and fruits.
They are best known for their low, guttural call which can be heard for several miles in the forest and is produced by pushing air through a specialized hollow hyoid bone in their throat that helps resonate the sound. They are the loudest terrestrial mammals in the Western Hemisphere and are fairly common in their native range.

Today, Jabari, one of the adult male lions at Zoo Miami, underwent his annual physical exam. As part of that exam, he had blood and urine collected, several radiographs, an ultrasound, a dental cleaning, vaccinations for rabies, canine distemper and feline distemper, as well as a mani/pedi. Other than some small skin lesions that were biopsied out of an abundance of caution, and being a bit on the hefty side (423 pounds), he is in relatively good health for a 16-year-old lion. He has since been returned to his habitat where he is recovering nicely. Here are some images that I was able to capture of the day's events.

Thanks to the thoughtfulness and generosity of @wildliferescueofdade , Founder and Director of @wildliferescuedadecounty , my wife, son and I had the privilege of releasing 3 rehabilitated hawks (a Cooper's hawk and two Red-shouldered hawks) back to the wild this morning, in honor of my late mother. I am privileged to sit on the Board of Wildlife Rescue of Dade County and have known Lloyd for decades (both of us went to Palmetto Senior High together). He and his team do amazing work in rescuing and rehabilitating hundreds of native animals every year and the Ron Magill Conservation Endowment is proud to support their incredible efforts. This morning was emotional for two very powerful reasons. First, it was a truly beautiful way to honor my mom who gave so much to all of us during her life. Second, it is profoundly rewarding to release such beautiful animals back to the wild where they belong. These birds had all been suffering from rodenticide which is secondary poisoning transferred by rodents that had ingested rodenticide and then were predated on and eaten by the hawks, passing it on to them. Please do not use these rodenticides because they are deadly way beyond the mice and rats that they are intended for. My most profound and heartfelt thanks to Lloyd and his team for the privilege that was bestowed upon me and my family this morning, but more importantly, for their dedication to rescuing and protecting native wildlife throughout our community.

For the past several days, “Berani,” Zoo Miami’s adult male Sumatran tiger, has been lethargic with a loss of appetite that has raised concern in the Animal Science and Animal Health teams at the zoo.

Yesterday, he was immobilized and transported to the zoo’s Animal Hospital so that he could undergo a series of exams to hopefully determine if a serious health issue was the cause of his abnormal behavior. These tests included radiographs, ultrasounds, blood and urine collection, and an endoscopy. Here are some images that I captured of the procedure as well as one of Berani in a healthier state.

Initial observations indicated that Berani was extremely anemic and dehydrated. Also noted, was an enlarged spleen as well as irregularities of the kidneys which could be a sign of renal failure. Kidney disease is a common issue with older cats, both domestic and wild. At over 15 years old, Berani is considered to be an old tiger (in the wild, their lifespan is usually between 10-15 years).

In addition to receiving significant amounts of IV fluids, he was also given a series of antibiotics, vitamins and pain medications with the intent of treating any possible infections as well as hopefully stimulating his appetite. He is being monitored around the clock to detect any changes in his condition. Pending the results of a variety of tests that were given, a medical plan will be determined to address whatever may be diagnosed.

There are believed to be less than 500 Sumatran tigers left in the wild where they are found in forested areas on the island of Sumatra in Indonesia. Their biggest threats are habitat loss to palm oil plantations and poaching. They are the smallest subspecies of tiger with males reaching up to 300 pounds and females closer to 200 pounds. Zoo Miami is one of the very few zoos in the world that has had success reproducing this critically endangered species.

It is with profound sadness that I inform you about the passing of “Berani,” the 15 ½ year old Sumatran tiger. As detailed in a previous post, Berani had been very lethargic and had lost his appetite over the last several days. In order to diagnose what may be the reasons for those issues, he was immobilized and brought to the zoo’s Animal Hospital on Tuesday for a series of examinations and tests.
Initial indications were that he was severely anemic and dehydrated. A series of procedures including radiographs, ultrasounds, blood and urine collection, and an endoscopy, were performed. Those procedures revealed an enlarged spleen as well as abnormalities of the kidneys. However, the Animal Health team needed to await the results of additional tests to be better able to diagnose what may be the cause of those abnormalities.
Late yesterday afternoon, test results revealed the heartbreaking news that Berani was suffering from cancer of the spleen. Sadly, due to his advanced age and an extremely poor prognosis for any improvement, the very difficult decision was made to humanely euthanize him to provide him the dignity in death that he displayed throughout his life.
Berani was born at the San Francisco Zoo in March of 2008 and came to Zoo Miami via the Montgomery Zoo in Alabama in 2013 as part of a Species Survival Plan (SSP) recommendation. He was paired with a female named “Leeloo” and successfully sired a male cub named, “Satu” in 2015 along with a female cub named, “Ndari” in 2021. In addition, as we sadly announce his passing, we will soon be announcing something much more uplifting that will only add to this magnificent cat’s legacy.
There are believed to be less than 500 Sumatran tigers left in the wild where they are found in forested areas on the island of Sumatra in Indonesia. Their biggest threats are habitat loss to palm oil plantations and poaching. They are the smallest subspecies of tiger with males reaching up to 300 pounds and females closer to 200 pounds. Zoo Miami is one of the very few zoos in the world that has had success reproducing this critically endangered species.

This past Saturday, a male Giant Eland was born at the zoo! Today, it had its neonatal exam and was then returned to the herd where it appears to be healthy and happy! Sunrise over the Pine Rockland this morning, the most critically endangered habitat in the entire state of Florida.  As I arrived at the zoo this morning, I just soaked in the serenity of this beautiful place.  I will continue to do all that I can to protect it. 🙏🏻🙏🏻🙏🏻

One of the greatest qualities one must have to be a wildlife photographer is patience. I am privileged to work at a place that is home to some of the most beautiful animals on earth. Giant Eland are the world's largest antelope and can only be seen in a handful of institutions. It is even rarer to experience multiple births. Within the last two weeks, Zoo Miami has had three of these beautiful animals born, two within the last two days! Newborns usually tuck in different areas to be protected from predation, so it is practically impossible to get a tight image with more than one of the newborns in it. I waited and waited and then the stars aligned, and all three babies stood up and walked towards each other where for a few precious moments, they were side by side surrounded by their mothers. I cannot express how much I love this!!!! #NaturePhotography #nikonusa #nikonnofilter #nikonambassador

It is hard for me to put into words the overwhelming emotions I am feeling this morning after yesterday's outcome at the Miami-Dade Board of County Commissioners meeting. For so long, I have felt the guilt of following directives from my supervisors and not speaking against the Coral Reef Commons project that resulted in precious acres of critically endangered pine rockland habitat being bulldozed for a WalMart, hundreds of apartments, an LA Fitness and other retail outlets. This time, against the directives of my supervisors, I spoke up against this water park project that was destined to be rubber stamped through to construction, never truly believing that it would make a difference but knowing that for my own self-respect, I could not stay silent again because that would make me complicit and a hypocrite as a wildlife conservationist. It wasn't until I spoke out that I realized how many people felt as I did! This is especially true of my peers at the zoo who have also dedicated their lives to conservation but could not voice their opinion out of fear of retribution. I also owed it to them to speak up on their behalf.
Having said that, I am receiving much more credit than I deserve in this effort. The people who deserve the credit are the scientists, researchers and volunteers who have spent countless hours gathering the data that enabled us to build the case against this project. It is groups like Bat Conservation International, Tropical Audubon Society and the Center for Biological Diversity, that provided the legal teams that were absolutely critical in bringing this case to the courts - and winning!! All I did was shine a light on all of this amazing work by so many and bring it to the forefront of people's attention.
Through this process, my faith in our Miami-Dade County government has been renewed and invigorated. Thank you to our Mayor and Commissioners for listening to our concerns and doing the right thing!

On Friday, December 15th, Zoo Miami welcomed the birth of an endangered babirusa, the first successful birth of this species in the history of the zoo! 
Of the over 20 different species of wild swine in the world, the unique babirusa is considered to be one of the most bizarre looking. The word “babirusa,” means “pig deer” in the Malay language. This is believed to come from the strange appearance of males whose tusks look like antlers growing on the top of its head. Unlike other pigs, the babirusa has a set of upper tusks that grow up through the top of its face and sometimes curl all the back into its head! These upper tusks, combined with a second set on the lower jaw that curl up and out away from the head, create an almost alien appearance that causes many to consider the babirusa the strangest looking pig in the world. Females do not exhibit these tusks while both sexes are relatively hairless.
Babirusas are found in the swamps and rainforests of Indonesia. They are omnivorous and feed primarily on fruits, roots, invertebrates, and small mammals, but will eat almost anything including on occasion, their own young. Here are some pics I was able to capture of mom and baby (sex undetermined), as well as the adult male. #babirusa #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikonambassador #wildpig

Here are some photos that I hope will bring smiles to your faces for the weekend! These are images that I was able to capture of Zoo Miami's baby sloth bear cubs during their first neonatal exam this past week. Born back on December 4th, this was the first time that the Animal Health Team was able to quickly examine the cubs for a general checkup and to determine their sexes. The cubs, both females, weighed between 2 and 3 pounds each and appear to be in good health. Mom was trained to station herself in a certain spot to receive treats while the staff was able to quickly separate the cubs for the exams. Everything went smoothly and mom and cubs are back together doing very well. They will remain off exhibit for several weeks while continuing to bond and getting acclimated to the world around them. 
Sloth bears are considered a vulnerable species that is threatened by poaching and habitat destruction. They are solitary and found in moist and dry forests of the Indian subcontinent where they feed primarily on fruit and insects – especially termites. There is a gap in their upper front teeth which enables them to create a straw with their long lips and suck up termites and other insects quickly and effectively. Their long shaggy coat does not have an undercoat, so it helps keep them cool in their native warm climate while protecting them from biting insects. 
I am incredibly grateful to my Nikon Z9 camera with its animal eye focus mode that quickly grabbed the focus of these constantly moving cubs in low light to capture these images! #slothbear #nikonphotography #nikonusa #nikonnofilter #nikonambassador

Today, the winning name of our Sumatran tiger cub was revealed! Her name is "Lani!" Recently, on my day off, it was rainy and cold and I figured it may be a good opportunity to get some images of Lani and her mother, Leeloo. I had gotten some decent images in the past of Lani on her own but I really wanted to get some images of mother and daughter together that would better reflect their personalities. Unfortunately, Leeloo doesn't like to come out when there are a lot of people or when it is sunny and warm. Knowing this, I went in to see what I could get. Sure enough, no one was at the zoo and I just sat in front of the Tiger Temple and waited. It wasn't long before Leeloo emerged and just laid down as a light rain fell, not paying any attention to my presence. Then the magic happened. Lani just started to jump and play all around Leeloo and Leeloo reciprocated with the patience and affection of a true mother. Here are some of the pics I was able to capture on that cold and rainy afternoon. It was hard for me to pic a favorite. Curious to know what yours is? Tips for photographers - sometimes rainy cold days are the best! #tigerlove #nikonnofilter #nikonusa #nikonambassador
